{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75634ffb-bdae-4f98-b226-9af197485c78","content":"Two things changed with xUnit v3 + MTP:\n\n1. **`--filter` (VSTest syntax) is no longer used.** MTP uses `--treenode-filter` instead.\n2. **Treenode filter syntax** uses glob-like paths and `[key=value]` for traits.\n\nYour old filter:\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nBecomes:\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]\"\n```\n\nBreakdown:\n| Old (VSTest) | New (MTP treenode) |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` | `/**/*IntegrationTests*` (glob at any depth) |\n| `Category=Smoke` | `[Category=Smoke]` (trait property filter) |\n| `&` (AND) | Combined inline — the glob and `[...]` are implicitly ANDed |\n\nArguments after `--` are passed directly to the MTP runner. No changes to your test code or `.csproj` are needed — the `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` attribute works the same in v3.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cd25076c-890d-42e8-8412-a189e5f72473","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP). The key changes are:\n\n1. With MTP (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`), the `--filter` syntax changes from VSTest filter syntax to MTP filter syntax.\n2. The old filter: `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke`\n\nIn xUnit v3 with MTP, the filter mechanism changes:\n- Instead of `--filter`, you use `--filter` but with different syntax, or you use `--treenode-filter`\n\n\n- With MTP, traits are exposed differently and the filter syntax uses a path-like structure like `/FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests[Category=Smoke]` rather than the VSTest syntax.\n\nWhen using `dotnet test` with MTP projects, the `--filter` option gets translated to `--treenode-filter` for the MTP runner, which uses patterns like `/**/<test-name>` for matching tests and `[key=value]` for filtering by traits or properties. I need to reconsider the filter syntax more carefully. The original `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke` uses a contains operator and AND logic, which translates to the MTP treenode filter `/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]` — matching any test path containing \"IntegrationTests\" with the Smoke category trait.","outputTokens":1185},"id":"412a21f3-9a1e-4538-a33e-bbc3bdbca422","timestamp":"2026-04-07T13:07:00.679Z","parentId":"793ad65a-4253-4fca-ae57-ab6da599ebe5"}
